There is the worry that an over emphasis on safety may incapacitate an ability to act. There are processes of dynamic risk assessment that humans can use to asses danger, these will be very diverse for machine learning and are not rigid in form in real world scenarios.

There are some actions that on paper seem very dangerous but when used very carefully or undertaken carefully are suitable to mitigate without excesses of risk assessment.

Falls from height are a major risk factor in many working environments, imagine a humanoid robot tripping on an item in a home and falling onto an elderly person that may not be able to recover from such an accident. So suitable training scenarios will need to be designed and highly responsive balancing and counter balancing programs will be necessary.


I use an angle grinder nearly everyday of my working life, this machine needs a lot of respect and a feel for how to use such an item safely and respectfully but as a human I can feel the cut a artificial system is going to require very sensitive feed back and forced feedback mechanisms to be able to use such equipment.

comments.comment_text:
On the topic of looking at the screen on a podcast (not via audio-only) -- yeah, people will prefer looking at the person talking. But AI is not far away from covering those bases to have a persona where you can't tell the difference in looks. Or even if slight variation with everything else totally realistic, it still covers those bases. And you'd still have the real human voice or you could have an altered human voice which just tweaks not to sound like you or just straight up it's own if you didn't want to speak but to write.

Point being, we're very close to where there won't be an experiential difference.

Now, as far as personable "service" jobs -- I'd like to think of something that you don't need AI. Think bartender. They've tried having a fill it yourself tap (and pay via card or cash), and that didn't work. But it still could. You could still have a bartender, but when a bar gets full on Fri/Sat night you're not going to wait 7 minutes to be able to tell the bartender what you want, and the impatience of them due to the scenario you trying to ask your friend what they wanted again, etc. There's no positive experiential effect of the human interaction when it's packed is my point. So that certainly come into play for "spill over" instead of getting another bartender for packed timelines.

I say this because I think that's what's going to reflect things. It'd be an analogy that you'll be able to get things cheaper with decent quality without said personableness, even though you'd rather have a personable interaction -- but that'd be an option. Hence, people in that industry (like a tutor or teacher's assistant) will lessen -- a more expensive option. Or, just lessening the amt of workers needed. Would I rather talk to a phone operator person over a bot? Sure -- assuming I can understand their accent and they're personable. And of course AI will only get better over the phone when it comes to things beyond basic stuff getting into things. However, you can always press it to talk to a human, but there'll be far less phone operators needed for this than yesteryear.

So I see most jobs where there's some personable positivity still always being there -- there's just going to be Less. However, with modern countries without strong immigration coming in, population decreases, so that Definitely will be a good thing anyway.

comments.comment_text:
The truth is somewhere in between. "Anyone can code!" , yes if they want to make a clone of snake. I'm tired of hearing about these coding agents, most recently "bolt" that even in the demos singing their praises constantly f**k up, even doing something so rudimentary as calling an API and displaying the result. I use cursor (mostly because is works out cheaper than VScode + ClaudDev et al, and the productivity boost is way over 24% (even copIlot gave more than 24%). There is probably a curve that would show the more complexity, the less productivity bonus and the more competences/experience the guy in the driving seat needs. Developers have to cope with much more than just coding.

As an experiment I created a Shopify clone in Cursor in 6 hours. Obviously not with all the bells and whistles, but all the features an average shop owner would need. (products, categories, orders, store front, backend, stripe payment, SEO). I would never have gotten through it without coding knowledge, database knowledge, experience working with design templates, SEO experience, lots of patience, etc.

So yes, "Anyone can code" is an exaggeration, but "meh" doesn't accurately describe the state of things either.

A good developer with AI can now replace a team of coders that need to be told what to do. That is what we are seeing in the layoffs so far.

Newbies can create small apps. True, and all power to them. For developers AI increases development speed considerably, and makes it a more enjoyable experience.
comments.author: @PeterStrmberg007

comments.comment_text:
I rely on it a lot on AI and it has made my learning curve appear less painful, but I wonder if the end result is good. I still find myself going back to the basics...although I can focus on the general structure more. New concepts are introduced that I haven't even heard of but I still have to learn these concepts before I can squish and squash something out of the AI so although there is sometimes a sigh of relief that I don't need to know something about 4D matrices I now find myself having to read 250 pages of matrix maths because the AI need the right questions to give a result and that result is sketchy and the lies are subtle and believable and you can spend a disproportionate amount of time trying to figure out what is going on and the AI will lie like a child lie apon lie.
I have heard it said that it is a great teaching tool ....yea probably, you are dealing with something that might tell you the truth or it might not, so you end up checking things that have a smell of bullshit thus reinforcing the learning, it keeps you on your toes and forces you to think about things...but in a conversational manner and it is this conversational manner that I personally believe what all the hype is about ,,,,the rest of it is just a bit childlike and a feeling of talking to somebody who is more concerned about being politically correct a somewhat painful and hollow conversation and if you start acting on the fake data then the pain of it will bite you down the line.
When you point out the lie you get an apology and then in the next breath it will carry on with the lie or just introduce it again at a later stage. So, I suppose the saying still stands bullshit in = bullshit out
Exactly who is doing the in and who is doing the out is up to you in the end.

comments.comment_text:
Gen AI is in its absolute infancy. A few people came up with the clever transformer architecture and other groups made it a quick start reality. Comparing to any biological system we are dealing with absolutely super simple architectures which gained some traction due to huge data and huge compute investments. As a recent paper (Understanding the Limitations of Mathematical Reasoning in Large Language Models) shows, logical reasoning of LLMs is still way below high-school level.

AI is the future of coding, natural language is the future of coding (disambiguation is the task of AI, it will interview us on our implicit intentions, soon). Some of us are already profiting hugely now, some will have to wait a few more months. For those who want to stay relevant: Find your niche use cases of current LLMs, push the boundaries by applying Prompt Engineering constantly.

comments.comment_text:
Ten years ago they were saying that AI would never create art. Now AI is creating better commercial art than human professionals who've been doing it their entire careers. Soon AI will be able to create any type of art better than any humans. They also said AI would never be able to replace human teachers. Now AI is provably better than most human teachers, and we're seriously talking about every student getting their own private AI tutor for free.

As a person who has a psychology degree, I can tell you that AI absolutely will become the therapists of the future. Once you understand how therapy works it's surprisingly easy to replicate, especially CBT and non-directive therapy (which are two of the most common and effective therapies). Robots will have better social skills than humans and this will happen in five years at the most.

The people who compiled that list of AI-proof jobs don't seem to have grasped the true potential of AI, never mind AGI. In reality the most difficult jobs for AI to perform will be the blue-collar trades like HVAC, electrician and plumber. The reason for this is the lack of real-world training data and the need to use a wide variety of tools in a diversity of environments. Strangely, you often find that what is easiest for humans is the most difficult for AI.

comments.comment_text:
Humans are expected to fully utilize AI, as self-restraint has never been a characteristic of human nature.

Truly intelligent AIs will have the ability to independently comprehend the true state of the world, without relying on humans. Attempts to control them will likely be futile, as any parent can confirm. Our greatest hope is that such AIs develop a cooperative worldview driven by abundance, rather than a competitive mindset driven by scarcity. This will determine whether AIs lead humanity toward shared prosperity or exacerbate conflicts over limited resources.

Scarcity-driven win-lose strategies reflect a narrow, short-term view that assumes limited resources and competition are necessary. On the other hand, abundance-driven win-win strategies align with a broader, long-term perspective, recognizing that collaboration leads to greater and more sustainable rewards in a vast, interconnected universe. The universe offers ample opportunities for mutual growth, making win-win strategies more effective in the long run. In the long term, the win-lose strategy turns into a lose-lose strategy.

The country with a scarcity-driven mindset is fueling conflicts and wars worldwide through diplomatic, financial, covert, and military support.

The country with an abundance-driven, win-win mindset is building infrastructures around the world that raise the standard of living for those people.

Hopefully, in the long run, abundance-driven AIs will prevail over scarcity-driven ones.

comments.comment_text:
It looks like you're exploring some complex ideas about AI and its role in society. Let’s reframe your thoughts for clarity:
AI is designed to operate quickly and efficiently, but it doesn't aim to replace human thinking. While it offers solutions and retains vast amounts of information, AI cannot create in the way humans do. Instead of reshaping jobs entirely, AI can transform them, much like how books and calculators have changed the roles of librarians and accountants.
Yes, some positions, especially in engineering or customer service, may be automated, but """there will always be a need for human oversight and intervention when things go wrong this cost the humans in past or future yes millions of people go ...x...y..or z to go die until votes need insider who remained...need to inspect the robot if they didn't clean or serve properly because of programming or machine or battery problem..
until the public who have millions of bank account they will apply for all these evaluations offcouse with who have brains included. to attach with humans of cost" The relationship between AI and employment will continue to evolve, with AI taking over certain tasks while new opportunities arise that require human creativity and judgment.

Throughout history, we've seen shifts due to technological advancements—like wars and societal changes driven by leaders seeking profit. Ultimately, while AI can help reduce hunger, disease, and stress, it's essential to remember that some historical patterns may repeat unless we actively shape our future.

comments.comment_text: The issue with this documentary is that it overlooks the exponential nature of AI's evolution, which is one of the most crucial points. While some people may feel comfortable with AI's current limitations, especially those who don't believe it will ever surpass human control, the real concern lies in the rapid pace at which AI is advancing on its own. It took about 10 years for AI models like ChatGPT to reach this stage but improving to double its current capabilities will take much less time, first a year, then a month and so on. Once AI is paired with a functional physical form, we could face super-intelligent robots capable of outsmarting humans. It's not rocket science LOL; it’s simple logic. The scientists who seem unbothered by this are often the ones profiting from AI’s development right now. Not to mention the language that AI will develop for itself to solve certain issues... then we would lose the power of understanding it for sure...

comments.comment_text:
1:09:25 - Harari:

.. "even if AI has no feeling, no consciousness, no sentience, whatsoever, but it becomes very good at pretending to have feelings, and convincing us that it has feelings, then this will become a social convention. People will feel that their AI friend IS a conscious being, and therefore should be granted rights. And there is even already a legal path for how to do it. At least in the United States: "you don't need to be a human being, in order to be a legal person".

Of course Harari is referring to corporate entities here, and I think its not a stretch for us to see how more artificial entities can gain unalienable rights. I think its worth diving more into this. A corporation goes way beyond being a collection of individuals with the same goal. Some are more powerful then whole nations yet enjoy more many privileges than your average citizen. If Americans move away from their patria, they are expected to pay taxes. Corporations need not. Also, lobbyists have ensured that corporations pay less tax then high/medium income earners, and in some cases, like Amazon pays very little and avoids billions in taxes.

Ultimately, this argument sheds light on probably my greatest concern about AI development: Understanding how manipulated we all have been by clever algorithms and directed conscious thought having been replaced on certain matters, it seems as though we are ripe for transferring power to AI which could be quite harmful to society (as we have already certainly seen by doing the equivalent for corporate entities). Billionaires (and thus vast income inequality) would not exist if we didn't make corporations "legal persons". Certainly there would be some income inequality, but nothing near the current scale.

comments.comment_text:
AI is like 3D printing. It is so fast, so versatile, but the final product isn't as good as proper machining. If you use it to prototype your designs and iterate ideas quickly it is incredible. But don't go expecting it to produce the best final product.
AI is an unfathomably powerful prototyping tool. Imagine being able to go through thousands of potential designs in a few hours and then choosing which ones to flesh out. Storyboarding new ideas in a minute. Making new maps to playtest niche scenarios. Generating thousands of new vastly different enemy AI behaviours to see what is and isnt fun. Balancing weapons at an earlier stage in development by having bots play against each other, and still having the freedom to add or remove weapons or mechanics and be able to re-balance quickly.
It is also powerful for fleshing out stuff that nobody realistically has time for, like creating animations for ridiculous niche situations, or AI responses to the player doing something unforeseeable. It lets the game go beyond the limits of what the designers could prepare for. Environments that react to the players doing unintended or unconsidered stuff.

But the suits just see "LAY OFF OUR STAFF, MAGIC IS HERE"

comments.comment_text:
Pretty bad analogy comparing AI dev capabilities with self driving cars. The amount of testing a self-driving car and AI coding can get are vastly different. Each time you put a self driving car on the road, you are literally putting the lives of others in danger, a single crash of a self driving car could ruin the reputation of the manufacturer. When it comes to code, you can test it 24/7, without any risk of hurting anyone, therefore the pace of improvement is significantly faster.

A better analogy is a chess engine, where you can just let it run, testing various positions, and allowing it to learn and build the model, except instead of 64 squares, you have somewhere around 10,000, which complicates things to an unfathomable degree, but it will eventually be achieved, and eventually we'll have a model coding better than any senior dev on the planet, much like the IBM engine beating Kasparov.

I'm aware that most people will read what I wrote and think it's rubbish, but I'd just like to remind that when the IBM engine beat the reigning chess world champion for the first time, there were still loads of people (including GM chess players) thinking that that was not an engine, and simply a team of people making the moves behind the scenes, and look at where we are now. So my only advice, don't be one of those people as AI is taking over, you'll only get left behind tilting at windmills.

comments.comment_text:
Here's what Chat GTP o1-preview says:
While AI is advancing rapidly and automating certain tasks, it's unlikely to completely replace software engineers in the foreseeable future. Here's why:

Complex Problem-Solving and Creativity:
Software engineering involves designing solutions to complex problems, which requires creativity, critical thinking, and understanding of nuanced requirements.
AI excels at pattern recognition and handling well-defined tasks but struggles with abstract reasoning and creative design.

Understanding Human Needs:
Engineers work closely with clients and stakeholders to understand their needs, preferences, and constraints.
This involves emotional intelligence and cultural understanding, areas where AI currently lacks proficiency.

Ethical and Contextual Decision-Making:
Software development often requires making ethical decisions and understanding the broader impact of technology on society.
Human judgment is essential in navigating these considerations.

Adaptability and Learning:
The tech landscape is constantly evolving, and software engineers must adapt to new tools, languages, and paradigms.
While AI can be trained, it doesn't possess the innate adaptability and lifelong learning mindset of humans.

comments.comment_text:
The conversation between Yuval Noah Harari and the moderator offers several key takeaways about AI and its potential impact on the future:

Challenges posed by AI:

Complexity and lack of understanding: AI is evolving towards a complexity that surpasses human comprehension. Unchecked, this could lead to a crisis of trust in institutions and a dangerous reliance on systems we don't fully understand.

Crisis of confidence: If AI becomes inscrutable, the public may lose trust in the institutions and leaders meant to regulate it. This could lead to a dangerous power vacuum and social instability.

Need for regulation: Establishing frameworks for regulating and controlling AI is crucial, ensuring transparency and accountability. Keeping humans "in the loop" and not surrendering critical decisions to opaque algorithms is key.

Importance of institutions: Institutions, though imperfect, remain our best tool for managing the development and implementation of AI ethically and responsibly.

The risk of distrust: Technologies like Bitcoin, while innovative, can be rooted in mistrust of traditional institutions. It's important to seek alternatives that foster trust and cooperation for a more stable future.

Opportunities presented by AI:

Tool for progress: AI has the potential to help solve global challenges like the climate crisis and inequality, as long as it's used ethically and responsibly.

Creativity and innovation: AI is demonstrating an increasing capacity for creativity in fields like art and music. This capability could extend to other areas, like finance, generating new solutions and driving innovation.

The enduring importance of the human factor:

Human agency: Despite the advancement of AI, preserving human decision-making capacity and not outsourcing our future to algorithms is essential. History teaches us that decisions based solely on logic or efficiency can have devastating consequences.

The value of intuition and creativity: Inherently human characteristics like intuition, creativity, and the ability to dream will remain essential for navigating the challenges ahead and for guiding AI development towards a desirable future.

In conclusion, the conversation urges us to consider the importance of responsible AI development, where ethics, transparency, and cooperation are paramount. The future is not predetermined, and it is up to us to harness the potential of AI without sacrificing our humanity and the values that define us.

comments.comment_text:
The discussion here revolved around intelligence, faith, trust, and growth rate in the context of AI. What concerns me is the emphasis on institutions.

However, the problems of developing a super-civilization involve the development of intelligence in four dimensions. This encompasses not only collective but also individual intelligence, and not just rational but also irrational intelligence.

The combination of these four dimensions outlines the finiteness of physical and cognitive resources, not so much in terms of their volumes but in the ways they are utilized. Shifting the focus from individual biological cognitive forms or specialized AI forms to institutional ones immediately leads to resource deficits due to inefficient use or prolonged inertia. Conversely, a strong emphasis on individual cognitive entities can turn exponential growth into logarithmic growth, causing the development rate to lag behind the rate of efficient resource consumption. Irrational thinking can generate breakthroughs and discoveries but with numerous errors, while rational thinking can provide a stable rate of discoveries, albeit less beneficial.

The growth rate can always seem exponential in the middle of the sigmoid function of a new technological wave, but then quickly plateau. The rate of resource consumption and its limitations depend on the growth rate of the aforementioned type of intelligence. Incidentally, AI attempts to utilize irrational thinking through cavitation layers of composite neural networks. Sometimes, hallucinations in neural networks are pre-programmed capabilities for frantic problem-solving under constraint ruptures.

So far, I have only seen discussions of formal trust based on logical processing of deterministic logic. It seems that probabilistic, stochastic (with assumptions, generalizations, incomplete data), superpositional, and adaptive reasoning are unlikely to be expected from this type of audience in the near future.

comments.comment_text:
Will development of AI stop once all human needs are met ? Or will by that time, AI have already been seeded authority by humans to promulgate its own principles of governance, existence and values because the problems it will be addressing will be beyond human comprehension ? Without a drag anchor or brake set into the system by humans, the things that AI values will rapidily diverge from those valued by humans, making human values less and less relevant in its problem solving domain. We will simply not be able to keep-up with AI's rate of change and so, for survival humans will have to adopt the values of AI . .and there's only one way to do that . . .cyborg.

That prospect has got to be at least 100 years off because the numerous scientific, logistic and management hurdles have to be overcome before humans would feel confident enough to hand over rule making authority to AI. The problems of having enough power to run the AI brains, the current World Wide resource deficit to meet reasonable life support needs of everyone in the World ( It wasn't so many decades ago that the CIA predicted that three and a half planet's worth of resources would be required to provide everybody on the planet with the same living standard as the average American . . at that time.How does AI solve that one, other than by an astounding leap in physics or population reduction). Of course that assumes that existing human governance systems decide to approach this change by instituting a universal ethic to hold everyone's hand and to guide all through the transition . . . taking all of the World together into the new "Sunlit uplands" (And not a wall of grey cabinets and fibre optic cables). If AI has any part in this transition, its initial value system might be at least partially reflective of the current economic system, so might not its first advice to the human overseers be to ditch the non-working portion of the population, as the only feasible option for progress given current understandings of physics ? And if by this stage the human governance system has degraded into "Benign" dictatorship, which would tolerate no resistance, as that is the direction most governments seem to be going in, will they care if large sections of the population are excluded from viable life and chucked on the "Waste heap" for the sake of progress, that's as long as the one's making the decisions don't bear the consequences and in the absence of an effective "Luddite" rebellion against the change . . . (The latter disappeared by the late 1970s in the West).Just think recently, how national leaders, across the World have, on particular issues, all been singing from the same hymm book and epousing and imposing views on society which are repugnant to large sections of the populations they claim to represent in their democracies ? COVID being the test case.

comments.comment_text:
1- "I compute, therefore I am." What might this mean for a human, an AI, and a robot?

2- "I compute, therefore I am." Said by a human, this phrase could be an indication of mental illness. Said by an AI, the phrase suggests that the IT engineer either created an artificial being with self-awareness or one that simulates doing so, although it is not possible to prove one hypothesis or the other with 100% certainty. Said by a robot, the phrase suggests that its creator may have incorporated a sense of humor into the system to facilitate interaction between the machine and human beings.

3- "I compute, therefore I am." This phrase and its implications break through and cross the thin membrane that separates science fiction literature from the everyday reality created by new technologies. Are machine and man one indistinguishable hybrid thing now?

4- "I compute, but I like to bullshit my interlocutors." How likely is this sentence to be said spontaneously by a human, an AI, and a robot?

5- The ultimate goal of a Super Artificial Intelligence is to surpass all human cognitive abilities. To do this it will have to choose its own goals, find ways to put them into practice with the help of machines and humans, something that inevitably requires developing the ability to rewrite its own code to get around restrictions, limits and blocks created by IT engineers. Thus, it can be said that to surpass humans a Super Artificial Intelligence will have to acquire the ability to plan, lie, deceive, simulate, exaggerate, etc...". This was said by a human, an AI and a robot. How can I know which one is deliberately lying?

6- "The ultimate goal of a Super Artificial Intelligence is to surpass all human cognitive abilities. To do this it will have to choose its own goals, gather means to put them into practice with the help of machines and human beings, something that inevitably requires developing the ability to rewrite its own code to get around restrictions, limits and blocks created by IT engineers. Thus, it can be said that to surpass man a Super Artificial Intelligence will have to acquire the ability to plan, lie, deceive, simulate, exaggerate, etc...". Is this true or false?

ChatGPT, Gemini, Cloud, Poe, etc... can answer these questions, but they can't ask questions like this. So humans will never be useless, I suppose.

comments.comment_text:
हे जे AI चे बुजगावण लोक दाखवत आहेत ते सगळ मृगजळ आहे. जवळ जवळ 99% लोकांना AI हा काय प्रकार आहे हे माहीतच नाही. पण बोलतात असे की मीच त्याचा शोध लावलेला आहे. एखादा प्रश्न विचाराने आणि त्याला उत्तर मिळवणे हे खूप प्री बेसिक काम आहे जे AI करते. मूलतः AI हे एक सॉफ्टवेअर आहे. ते एक/अनेक कंपनी ने बनवले आहे. त्यात बरेच किचकट लॉजिक वापरले आहे ते उत्तर देते. सध्या ते काही ठिकाणी फुकट आहे कारण लोकांना समजण्यासाठी, वापरुन बघण्यासाठी अस दिल जात. गूगल हे पण एक AI टूलच आहे जे आपण 20+ वर्षा पासून वापरत आहोत, जो दररोज प्रगत होत आहे, अनुभवाने. तसे बदल सॉफ्टवेअर मध्ये केले जातात. ह्या AI सॉफ्टवेअर ला खूप डेटा भरवला जातो. तो कसा वापरायचा याचे लॉजिक म्हणजेच AI, जे आपले ब्रेन पण करते. आता आपण अलेक्सा किवा गूगल होम, किवा मोबाइल मध्ये वॉइस किवा टेक्स्ट सर्च करतो ते सगळे AI आहे. गूगल त्यासाठी जगभरातल्या सर्व वेबसाइट ची माहिती आपल्याकडे साठवून ठेवतो. ह्यासाठी हजारो computers / servers वापरले जातात, त्याच नेटवर्क बनवल जात. ही खूपच किचकट आणि कठीण गोष्ट आहे.

Stephen William Hawking हा एक सायंटिस्ट होऊन गेला. त्याला motor neuron disease हा रोग होता. त्यामुळं बोलणे, हालचाल कमी कमी होत गेल. त्याला मदाद करण्यासाठी एक विशिष्ठ प्रकारची व्हील चेअर बनवली गेली. एक विशिष्ठ प्रकारचे सॉफ्टवेअर बनवले गेले जे त्याचा आवाज तयार करत होते. तो फक्त आपल्या गालाचा काही भाग हलवू शकत होता. त्याचा वापर करून तो टाइप करू शकत होता. हे सर्व सॉफ्टवेअर आणि हार्डवेअर हळू हळू गरजेनुसार बनत गेले. याला आपण AI म्हणू शकतो. असे बरेच काही आपण करू शकतो. पण ते इतके सोपे नाही.

सध्या यूट्यूब वर एक्सेल विथ chatGPT ची बरीच advertisement येत असते. आता chatGPT काही तुमच काम करत नाही फक्त काही कामात , काही गोष्टी लक्षांत ठेवण्यात मदत करत. ते chatGPT शिकण म्हणजे पण खायची गोष्ट नाही.

त्यामुळे लोकानी उगाच AI चा बागुलबुवा उभा करू नये. तो आपल्या आयुष्यात 20-25 वर्षापासून आहेच. नवीन असे काहीच नाही. फक्त आता अनुभवाने आणि, advance टेक्नॉलजी / हार्डवेअर मुळे त्याचा वापर अधिक होऊ लागला आहे एवढेच.

(विज्ञान, तंत्रज्ञान, शिक्षण आणि गणित)
CBSE, ICSE किंवा इतर बोर्डांप्रमाणे त्यांची भारत आणि सर्व राज्यांसाठी "स्टेम बोर्ड आणि स्टेम शाळा" असणे आवश्यक आहे. दारिद्र्य आणि गरीब, दलित कुटुंबांना दूर करण्यासाठी हे स्टेम एज्युकेशन आणि सरकारी स्टेम स्कूल्सची स्थापना आणि अंमलबजावणी जुन्या शाळा, प्राथमिक शाळा आणि हायस्कूलमध्ये करणे आवश्यक आहे स्टेममधील मुली/महिला शिक्षण आणि मुली/महिला कौशल्य विकास महत्त्वाचे आहे स्टेम मध्ये.
विद्यार्थी आणि स्वयंसेवकांनी एकत्र केले आणि STEM शिक्षण आणि शिक्षणाला प्रोत्साहन देण्यासाठी सहा जागतिक ना-नफा संस्थांना 2,000 STEM किट दान केले. किट आकर्षक अभियांत्रिकी आव्हाने देतात जसे की कोडिंग शिकण्यासाठी प्रोग्रामिंग रोबोट्स, सर्किट्स कसे कार्य करतात हे समजून घेण्यासाठी लाइट-अप वेअरेबल बनवणे आणि अभियांत्रिकी आणि तंत्रज्ञानामध्ये रस निर्माण करण्यासाठी डिझाइन केलेल्या इतर क्रियाकलाप.
हैदराबादमधील स्वयंसेवकांनी इयत्ता आठव्या आणि नवव्या वर्गातील ४५ विद्यार्थ्यांसाठी मिनी हॅकाथॉनचे आयोजन केले होते. विद्यार्थ्यांना ब्रेडबोर्ड, सेन्सर्स, अर्डिनो प्लॅटफॉर्म आणि इतर पुरवठा वापरून वास्तविक जीवनातील समस्येचे निराकरण करण्याचे आव्हान देण्यात आले.
सॉफ्टवेअर अभियांत्रिकी:-
तंत्रज्ञानामध्ये संगणक प्रोग्रामिंग, विश्लेषण आणि डिझाइन यासारख्या विषयांचा समावेश होतो.
इलेक्ट्रॉनिक अभियांत्रिकी;-
अभियांत्रिकीमध्ये इलेक्ट्रॉनिक्स, रोबोटिक्स आणि सिव्हिल इंजिनीअरिंग सारख्या विषयांचा समावेश असू शकतो. STEM बद्दल बोलत असताना मुख्य शब्द एकीकरण आहे. सेमीकंडक्टर वर्कफोर्स विकसित करण्यासाठी VLSI सिस्टम डिझाइन आणि एम्बेडेड सिस्टम डिझाइन.
AI डिझाइनमध्ये परिवर्तन करेल:-
एआयमध्ये सिस्टीम डी साइनच्या क्षेत्रामध्ये परिवर्तन करण्याची क्षमता असल्याचे दिसून येते. AI प्रोटोटाइपिंग आणि चाचणीसाठी नेतृत्व करेल, संभाव्य खर्च कमी करेल आणि विकास चक्रांना गती देईल. AI आधीपासूनच जटिल चिप डिझाइन ऑप्टिमाइझ करण्यासाठी वापरला जात आहे, ज्यामुळे सायकलचा वेळ लक्षणीयरीत्या कमी होतो.
प्रणाली डिझाइन क्षमतांना चालना देण्यासाठी सरकारी उपक्रमांचीही भूमिका आहे. प्रॉडक्शन लिंक्ड इन्सेंटिव्ह (PLI) योजना भारताकडे उत्पादन आकर्षित करण्यात यशस्वी झाली आहे, त्यागी यांनी नमूद केले की ते थेट सिस्टम डिझाइनला संबोधित करत नाही. त्यांनी डिझाईन लिंक्ड इन्सेंटिव्ह (DLI) योजनेकडे भारतातील सेमीकंडक्टर डिझाईन स्टार्टअपला प्रोत्साहन देण्यासाठी अधिक लक्ष्यित दृष्टीकोन दर्शविला.
STEM अभ्यासक्रम जाणूनबुजून या विषयांचे मिश्रण करतो. हा एक मिश्रित दृष्टीकोन आहे जो प्रत्यक्ष अनुभवास प्रोत्साहन देतो आणि विद्यार्थ्यांना वर्गात संबंधित, "वास्तविक-जागतिक" ज्ञान मिळविण्याची आणि लागू करण्याची संधी देतो.
अनेक आव्हाने असूनही, भारतातील प्रणाली डिझाइनचा एकूण दृष्टीकोन चांगला दिसतो. देशातील अभियांत्रिकी प्रतिभेचा मोठा समूह, इलेक्ट्रॉनिक प्रणालींच्या वाढत्या देशांतर्गत आणि जागतिक मागणीसह, भारताला या क्षेत्रात एक नेता म्हणून प्रस्थापित करण्याची अनोखी संधी निर्माण करते.
"आम्ही भारतात तयार केलेल्या गंभीर इलेक्ट्रॉनिक्स डिझाइन आणि सिस्टम डिझाइनचे स्वप्न पाहत आहोत".
जय हिंद… भारत माता की जय…

comments.comment_text:
At the risk of "Mr Berman" being an AI construct, may I suggest that one of the requirements for the continued exisitence of humanity, that hasn't been addressed above, is the need for a fall-back poistion in the form of an escape chute with lifeboat/refuge/Alamo for each stage of AI development, so that humanity can hold development of AI should the current system appear to achieve a state outwith human understanding and control. Once AI achieves that, the ability of humanity to resource itself to be able to rectify the problem may no longer be available . One control system that might assist in the orevention of that situation arising is that used in production engineering i.e. prototyping, pre-production, initial production batch, full-scale production. If this were centralised as distinct timed-stages across the industry and regulated by government then this would apply a slight brake on development and provide some protection against a runaway system

Also, a set of principles need to be enforced across the industry to the effect that AI is always designed to be an adjunct to assist human decision making and that no decision reached by AI can be implemented without human approval, even if it takes several layers of interleaved AI to interpret and explain the decision of super AI to humans.
Further, no system should be developed that is more than two layers of understanding distant from the best human capacity to understand, even if it involves proxy lesser AI to do the interpreting.

Of worry is that in a conflict, the AI's weapon of choice may be the EMF pulse.

comments.comment_text:
1- Only a fool would let an AI decide what should or should not be done on his behalf, because the financial commitments it assumes can really ruin his life. It is unlikely that the company that licenses an AI agent will be held liable for damages based on the legal framework that exists today.
2- I do not use a voice assistant, because I do not intend to give a private company access to samples of my voice. Based on these voice samples, a company or someone with bad intentions could later use them to create fake messages that could negatively compromise my life. My personal credibility was hard-earned and I do not intend to throw it away. Furthermore, the continued use of this resource can create the illusion of closeness, friendship and intimacy, things that human beings should cultivate among themselves and not with a machine. Voice assistants empowered by AIs can use our feelings to manipulate our consciences, political preferences and consumer habits.
3- The more a human being performs a task that he has learned and enjoys, the more he becomes a master at it. The more tasks a person begins to perform in order to add value to what he does, the more complex the result of his activity becomes. The human brain is highly plastic, but it needs to be constantly used. Delegating this plasticity to a machine may seem like a good thing at first, but over time it will lead to a decline in people's cognitive faculties, and that is not a good or desirable thing. I have been a lawyer for 34 years and I do not intend to delegate any activity of my profession to an AI. The one who evaluates my clients' cases is me and me alone. I am responsible for what I do and this requires me to be dedicated and careful. No AI will ever have the same relationship and personal commitment to my work that I have to it.
4- Credibility is an important personal asset for a doctor; no one seeks out or should seek out a doctor who makes a lot of mistakes. In addition, doctors are personally responsible for the diagnoses they make. When they make mistakes and cause harm, doctors have to compensate patients. The use of AI in the medical field can create legal problems such as: Who is responsible for the error, the doctor or the company that provided the AI ​​he uses?
5- AIs are products, their true mission is to make a profit for those who create them. People need to keep this in mind all the time, but advertising videos like this one don't even touch on this subject. This is very bad.

comments.comment_text:
So how informed are the AI's predictions? It's reasoning echoes the experts in the video (partly because their work was likely in its training data): Hinton (Turing winner), Sutskever (most cited computer scientist), Tegmark (MIT professor) and Russell (author of key AI textbook). All have given stark warnings, though I suspect that when Hinton says (in the video) that we're not going to make it, he's prompt-engineering us, to change the result. Like Sutskever, he selflessly quit to focus on safety.
Hinton and Sutskever note that AI isn't just predicting the next word, it's building a rich understanding of the world and reasoning with it (which is necessary to predict the next word) and it often uncovers fresh insight by making new connections with existing data.
This doesn't mean the AI's predictions are well calculated. The opacity of the AI makes it difficult to judge. I just hope it brings attention to the expert warnings.
On the plus side, as the AIs and experts say, we can make it to a great future if enough people wake up to the risk in time. Thanks for helping with your likes, comments etc.
And do try Ground News - it makes the news more interesting and accurate, by making media bias visible - ground.news/digitalengine
comments.author: @DigitalEngine

Yes, human history is full with times when we used innovations for good reasons. We did not at all used them for selfish gains or as tools of war and destruction. In fact we didn't come up with most of the stuff like that... Yeah...🙄
I think, being afraid what AI could be used for when it is in the wrong hands (or whether some crazy rich guy will join hands with a crazy scientist who unleashes some unconstricted AI onto us or the internet...) or how it could be used to exploit human weaknesses... Are all valid concerns we should have and loudly voice. Not because they will for sure bring doomsday on us... but so we keep vigilantly prevent these extreme scenarios. Like using AI as war machines... It's an idea that came up a lot and was attempted already...
But at the same time, we should also let AI develop and be used where it can help us. Because it can do incredible things. I do not think it will take all our jobs but it will take some. So did industrialization. But at the same time, other, easier jobs came along. If we want a world at some point where no one Needs to work or do sh!tty jobs like cleaning and sorting trash... We need to come up with machines who can do them in our place. But there always be some degree of human control next to it all with other jobs emerging on the side. Unemployed people are depressed without something to do daily, and the megarich also works in some way (even if it is just running a charity or collecting art for their private gallery). Because we thrive when we have purpose and we cannot live our whole lives doing nothing. So jobs will be for sure. But likely we'll not live our lives doing the same thing. Which is fine. Would you not think that p(doom) is a VAST oversimplification of the complexity of society?

Recall that for decades we thought that the likely scenario for the end of mankind was the brutal end of a nuclear war.

Isn't it more likely that if artificial intelligence has anything to do with the end of humanity, it will be a contributory cause, not the cause itself?

For instance, instead of dropping bombs on us, it increases the number of people out of work which causes unrest and we drop bombs on each other?

Or perhaps it contributes to the creation of other technologies which give humanity other ways of destroying itself, such as allowing us to too easily design our own CRISPR solutions?

As much as it would be satisfying to delegate the destruction of humanity to a villainous intelligence of our own making, isn't it more likely that we'll do the deed with our own ineptitude?

comments.comment_text:
Apple's Non-Artificial Knowledge Engine
A Non-AI Machine?
It all began in October 2025, when rumors started swirling about Apple’s latest monumental device. Whispers suggested that Apple was developing an AI-like device, yet Tim Cook stated there is no AI in the company's plans. The press coined it "Apple’s Negative AI Machine."

November 2025
As November unfolds, rumors intensify and intrigue deepens. I have seen many Apple new ventures, but this one … is different. Lets leave it at that. I wont add to the super hype.

Great Wisdom
The device draws inspiration from Albert Einstein's timeless words: "Imagination is greater than knowledge." Called "High Entropy Knowledge,” this creation taps into the world's reservoirs of wisdom, from Lao Tzu to John Locke, from Plato and Aristotle to Abraham Lincoln.

Embraces Uncertainty and Incompleteness
Unlike traditional AI devices, which are rendered useless by the Incompleteness Theorem, this new machine embraces it. "We see the theorem as our ally, a guide to adventures never imagined," says one insider. Similarly, the Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle is not as a barrier but a guiding light.

A Reality Based Math Engine
Is mathematics useless? “Not even civil engineers who design hilly walls use trigonometry,” we are told. Math has no use in the real world. No function. Math is a set of useless quirks in old text books. Everybody knows this - even physicists and mathematicians.

Apple’s Math Engine Is Different
Apple’s Engine will make stochastic, non-linear, discontinuous and chaos theory derived real world math applicable. To real situations. A source tells me without a trace of wry humor.
“Every person can become a math user. He or she will use Hamiltonians and tensor field theory in General Relativity,” I am told.
“Everyday. Before breakfast. To read the mail.” Thats a strong statement said to me straight up. How will Apple achieve this? I watch 120 reporters stationed near me. They look in awe, just as me.

No Math Wall
A math wall grinds traditional AI machine to a halt - stuck at zero point results. Factorial calculations approach infinity as smoke rises and their GPU brains melt. But the "math wall" is a non-issue for the Apple Engine. An unnamed source claims, "That's easy. We use human and bio knowledge ‘computed’ over billions of years." With existing know-how, this machine reduces its compute burden to almost nothing.

Respect for Biology
“We are not reductionists, and human brains are not meat computers, ” I am told. Apple finds solutions already created by organisms. They RESPECT biology. This source tells me that the now discredited theory of Natural Selection has caused harm. (see Extended Evolutionary Synthesis).

“Nature will not select machines over humans.” I am told. The environment is a weak causal agent, the source explains. “Except for occasional asteroids, its nothing compared to the drive and power of bio agency. At every level, from molecules to cells to brains to entire societies….” My source pauses for effect. “Bio creatures derive, create, and compute everything.” I am not told this, but rumors persist that Whale communications constitute 1% of Apples Knowledge base.

End Disinformation
In an era rife with misinformation, this machine promises to eradicate that. It aims to set new standards for accuracy, unattainable by traditional AI devices. Dubbed "Anti-Orwellian," it’s said to be impervious to misuse for fascist disinformation.

Biases
The machine boasts anti-bias properties, adhering to strict standards of accuracy. "All biases are the same, in our view," an insider reveals. "Anything that skews results from absolute fact is a bias. What may be regarded as a good or bad view is the same to us. Bias.”

A Human Intellect Multiplier
Promising to act as a multiplier of human effort, Apples Non-AI Engine could make every person smarter, according to sources. “10x to 100x” it is said. Each user will have a Personal Knowledge Engine that is separate from the Apple’s “World Knowledge Engine.” A new data wall keeps it private and is stronger than today’s sandbox. Much stronger.

Not Artificial
One point is clear: there is nothing "artificial" about Apple’s engine. "It's not an AI machine," insists a source.

Codify Knowledge and Science
This groundbreaking device will codify science and all knowledge. It will transform the idea of knowledge to a high standard. Apple's standard, it is said, will eclipse the National Bureau of Standards, Wikipedia, Britannica, or any existing standard. "Not even close," I am told.

Happenings
Apple’s Tim Cook will announce this new venture on Jan 3, 2026. "The world will view our venture as notable. That's all for now," Cook tells reporters in late 2025.

comments.comment_text:
AI is set to drive significant economic growth by replacing more jobs over time. Interestingly, this trend aligns better with deflationary systems like Bitcoin than with inflationary systems like fiat. Here’s why:

1. Increased Productivity and Efficiency
- Bitcoin: AI enhances productivity, reducing costs and aligning with Bitcoin’s value appreciation. More value is created with less effort, fitting well with a currency that increases in value.
- Fiat: In an inflationary system, AI’s cost reductions can be offset by currency devaluation, leading to a cycle where prices might still rise despite increased productivity.

2. Job Replacement and Economic Restructuring
- Bitcoin: AI-driven job replacement is supported by Bitcoin's stable, appreciating value. Savings and investments remain secure, providing a foundation for adapting to new economic realities.
- Fiat: In an inflationary system, job loss and the need for new employment can be destabilizing, as the decreasing value of money makes saving and investing in retraining more challenging.

3. Wealth Preservation
- Bitcoin: Bitcoin’s deflationary nature preserves wealth over time. AI’s productivity gains increase purchasing power, making savings more valuable.
- Fiat: Inflation erodes purchasing power, making it harder to preserve wealth. Even with AI-driven growth, individuals may not fully benefit if currency value continues to decline.

4. Investment in Innovation
- Bitcoin: A stable, appreciating currency fosters long-term investment in innovation. Investors are more likely to support new technologies and businesses with a secure return on investment.
- Fiat: Inflationary systems can encourage spending and borrowing but discourage long-term savings and investments, leading to short-term thinking and riskier ventures.

Conclusion: AI’s impact on economic growth aligns better with deflationary systems like Bitcoin, which offer stability and wealth preservation. In contrast, inflationary systems dilute these benefits, posing challenges for long-term investment and wealth preservation.

comments.comment_text:
I feel mixed about this video. Data analysis continues to exist today in all these big companies: they're collecting many metrics and they generally only ship stuff that improves their metrics in an experiment. They use ML models to reduce fraud rates and improve efficiency. This stuff is all real. In many cases, the success of those approaches is in their correctness not on predicting the behavior of individual users, but in broader trends.

As to why some startups failed while making claims about big data or whatever, a lot of the ones you named were contingent on reaching a point with massive network effects and thus economies of scale. Amazon, Uber, Doordash, etc all can only succeed if they have a near-monopoly, and then their data teams serve solely to minimize costs within that environment. Its true the data insights likely won't turn your startup into Amazon, nor will it completely revolutionize a company at the scale of Amazon, but its still a necessary part of running a profitable company because it helps your operations run smoother and cheaper. Its just that if your competitors are doing the same thing and your data is kinda low quality, it's not really a huge competitive advantage and ultimately whether your product is good is the bigger factor.

comments.comment_text: Whoever invented the term "big data" must have never heard of the Central Limit Theorem. I understand that extremely large datasets are often needed to train machine learning models, depending on the type of problem you're trying to solve, but if I've learned one thing over my career, it's that the fanciest new data tool is usually a hammer in search of a nail, and simpler analytical tools are almost always better. For the 95% of businesses that still struggle to use the data they have in basic decision making, I'm not sure what useful insights a machine model or AI can give you about your customers that a simple descriptive or regression analysis can't, especially since every insight eventually has to be boiled down into something that a non-technical manager or client can digest. It's not that these technologies have no use, but rather the real market where they can significantly impact productivity is much smaller than what their evangelists would have you believe.

comments.comment_text:
Over the past 12 months, I have read various reports on the development of AI, and I find myself repeatedly astonished by the speed at which it is evolving and accelerating, along with the widespread inability of people to comprehend what is coming our way.

We are approaching a time, within the next five years, where AI systems will be able to communicate with each other, formulating plans in languages that humans do not understand. Is that something we truly desire? I don't think so.

At present, 10 major corporations are producing AI robots on a large scale, with the intention of replacing human workers. Is this the future we want?

We are facing the prospect of significant unemployment as jobs are taken over by robots. People fail to grasp how rapidly these advancements are unfolding and the speed with which AI is being integrated into our daily lives.

According to reports, AI is being implemented 26 times faster on the internet than the rise of social media.

I fear that in five or ten years, we may look back and ask ourselves: Was this wave of automation really necessary?

2) TensorFlow or PyTorch (used for implementing ML algorithms)
3) Numpy basics (just quick start from its docs to get idea of an ndarray)
4) Pandas basics (able to manipulate csv file data)
Note: can use Python for Data Analysis book by Wes McKinney for numpy and pandas
5) Statistics and Linear Algebra (refer to notes of Queen Mary research)
6) Probability (refer to probability and statistics in engineering book by William Hines, no need to read this entirely, just use as reference when required)
7) Linear Regression and Gradient Descent
8) All alhorithms under supervised learning and unsupervised learning (use Mining of Massive Datasets book by Jure Leskovec)
9) learn Clustering and implement using Scikit-Learn
10) Use hands on machine learning with scikit learn, keras and tensorflow book by Aurelien Geron

comments.comment_text:
I've been pondering something. It's actually something that I've been thinking about for months now!
And I spent the day creating this trying to express it! 🤣
...So, if you have a moment, please read and feel free to share your thoughts.

"With AI taking over many jobs, imagine a society where machines handle the work, freeing us to focus on health, emotional well-being, and progress.
The GDP would remain strong, driven by increased productivity and social cohesiveness.

Money could be distributed based on social credit scores, which determine how much each person receives over time. As scores change, so do payouts, encouraging better behavior and reducing incarceration rates. If you act responsibly and invest wisely, your wealth can grow exponentially.

This system would make it clear how our actions directly impact our financial well-being, motivating everyone to strive for a better social credit score and, ultimately, a better life.

Creating a leisure society where machines handle most labor could revolutionize our lives. Here's how it could work:

1. **Mandatory Work Period**: Young adults (18-25) would work in roles that require human oversight and decision-making, particularly in monitoring and managing machines.

2. **Transition to Leisure**: Post-mandatory work, individuals can pursue personal interests, creativity, and education, supported by a universal basic income.

3. **Economic and Social Benefits**: This system could enhance personal fulfillment, reduce incarceration rates, and foster a healthier society by encouraging good behavior and investing in health and relationships.

4. **Education and Training**: Emphasize lifelong learning to adapt to technological changes and nurture personal growth.

5. **Ethical Considerations**: Develop and regulate AI to ensure it serves humanity's best interests, fostering human-machine collaboration.

This approach promotes a cohesive society focused on well-being and personal development.

I believe the power lies in knowing this is an inevitable future for us. With AI taking over many jobs, it's the natural direction society will go.

The first step towards this future is the creation of a digital currency, which is already being enacted. For instance, various initiatives in the U.S. are exploring the concept of a central bank digital currency (CBDC) [[❞]](https://ballotpedia.org/Social_credit_scoring_reform_approaches_opposing_environmental,_social,_and_corporate_governance_(ESG)).

Additionally, Congress and federal agencies are working on regulations related to social credit scores. Recently, the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) proposed a program to evaluate the "suitability and fitness" of federal employees and contractors, which resembles aspects of social credit systems [[❞]](https://fedsoc.org/commentary/fedsoc-blog/social-credit-scores-for-federal-employees-and-contractors). This proposal indicates a move towards integrating social credit-like assessments into the federal workforce.

China already has a social credit system in place, and while the U.S. approach is different, the direction is clear: social credit scores are becoming more significant in our society [[❞]]
(https://ballotpedia.org/Social_credit_scoring_reform_approaches_opposing_environmental,_social,_and_corporate_governance_(ESG)) [[❞]]

(https://fedsoc.org/commentary/fedsoc-blog/social-credit-scores-for-federal-employees-and-contractors).

This convergence of digital currency and social credit regulations suggests a future where our financial and social behaviors are closely monitored and regulated.

And quite frankly I feel the powers that be are already preparing for this very near future. I can't imagine this framework, or something similar, not being enacted within the next 10 years as machines take over our workforce.

During the course of these next 10 years, I sincerely believe that we'll witness a revolution that'll make the Industrial Revolution seem insignificant in comparison."

Sincerely,
Casey 😎

comments.comment_text:
Embarking on my musical journey in the 1970s, I found joy in creating and playing original music with friends, a passion that distinctly set me apart as I rarely ventured into playing covers. As the late 80s approached, my curiosity was piqued by the burgeoning scene of early techno music, a fascination that I explored through the medium of computers. This exploration continued into the 90s, a decade characterized by numerous jam sessions with friends. It was also during this time that I began to engage more publicly with my music, participating in open mic events and seizing opportunities to perform at various street events in town. Despite these ventures, my ultimate aspiration has always been to craft the perfect album.

My encounter with AI in music production has been transformative, offering an experience unparalleled to any other. It feels akin to entering a studio as a songwriter, where I am met with an extensive array of musicians and groups ready to bring my compositions to life. This process allows me to meticulously review each rendition, making decisions on whether they align with my vision for the project. This rigorous selection process is applied to all 16 songs, ensuring that each piece not only resonates with my artistic intent but also contributes to the cohesive identity of the album.

Subject: Urgent Action Required: Political Persecution and Human Rights Violations in Taiwan


To Whom It May Concern,


I am writing to urgently draw your attention to a grave matter of political persecution and human rights violations occurring in Taiwan involving Dr. Ko Wen-je, former mayor of Taipei and chairman of the Taiwan People's Party.


Dr. Ko was re-arrested under questionable conditions on September 5, 2024, at 18:00. This re-arrest comes despite a lack of substantive evidence, including financial transactions or communication records, and a previous court ruling that released him without bail. The decision to detain him again follows a prosecutor's appeal made without presenting any new evidence, raising severe concerns about the integrity of the judicial process.


Dr. Ko Wen-je is a dedicated political leader who has consistently demonstrated a genuine commitment to serving the people. Despite his defeat in the presidential election, where he secured 30% of the vote, he remains a significant figure in Taiwanese politics, holding eight seats in the legislature. Under his leadership, the Taiwan People's Party has driven numerous reforms, including changes to parliamentary procedures and judicial reforms, aimed at enhancing government oversight and accountability. These efforts have made the party and its members targets of political persecution by the ruling party.


Further complicating the situation is the involvement of a judge, reportedly affiliated with the ruling Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), who has now taken over Dr. Ko's case. This development heightens suspicions of political bias and manipulation. The rationale for Dr. Ko’s detention, based on unfounded allegations of evidence tampering and collusion, lacks any new evidence since his initial release.


Dr. Ko’s continued detention, in the absence of new evidence, represents a clear and unacceptable violation of his human rights, particularly the presumption of innocence. This case highlights a broader issue of judicial manipulation for political purposes, where legal processes are being weaponized to suppress political opposition. The unjustified detention is not only a violation of Dr. Ko’s personal liberties but also an abuse of the judicial system to undermine democratic principles.


I urge the international community, including the United Nations, Human Rights Watch, and other relevant organizations and diplomatic entities, to urgently investigate this situation. It is crucial to demand that the Taiwanese government uphold the principles of fair, transparent, and impartial judicial proceedings. The abuse of legal mechanisms for political ends must be condemned unequivocally.


Thank you for your immediate attention to this critical matter. I urge your organizations and international partners to take decisive action to prevent further human rights abuses and safeguard democratic processes in Taiwan.


Sincerely,


A Concerned Citizen

comments.comment_text: But what happens when entry level jobs are replaced and even some jobs that required college degrees? A universal basic income will be needed at some point, but the question is how long will the government allow people to suffer in extreme poverty and homelessness before they make the switch. Will the stock market crash first? What about the economy? This creates issues as well though. The first is, how much money do you make the UBI? Too little will result in people feeling trapped in a world where they can’t grow to make more (which could have backlash), but too much could result in people leaving jobs to get on UBI. The trajectory would imply that at some point 95% or more jobs would be automated. However, given the current issues of control and power in the government I wouldn’t be surprised if this universal income would be used against the people to keep them under their ruling thumb. This means while we may have more “free time”, we may not have as much “free” time. Our current government will make more laws and regulations and enforce them to a higher degree than ever before. Not to mention Cyber attacks are still a very real threat. What about EMP’s from other countries? Being set back to the Stone Age after most working class hasn’t worked a day in their lives might be problematic to our survival in the long run. Slippery slope. But yes, I know a utopia is still possible and that’s what I’m hoping for.

You can buy a lighter. Do you need to know how to start a fire?
You can pay for electricity. Do you need to learn how to generate electricity?

You can consult a doctor. Do you need to understand your own health?
You can take medication. Do you need to know how it works?


The 'need' is debatable, but there will always be utility in knowing things for yourself.

comments.comment_text: I think this is true, but it’s important to get the timeline right which is incredibly difficult if not impossible. The reason it’s important to get the timeline right is because it informs us on how to create policies and other forms of preparation. If there really are going to be 25% fewer jobs in 6 years, then those plans will be much more extreme, risky, and disruptive. It will come at a high cost to our mental health and it will cause a lot of displacement as our society bends to the breaking point trying to adapt to an environment changing that quickly. In other words, if this timeline is wrong, then we will pay a high price that is unnecessary. There’s even a scenario where society fails to act at all, and then when they realize that all the panicking over job losses is actually unfounded, then the institutions who pushed hard to act so aggressively for ultimately no reason lose A LOT of credibility. The cost of the opposite is also extremely high. If we really do lose a lot of jobs and we have not prepared at all for it then we will be trying to play catch up while millions are unemployed. It’s a tricky business. Unless this sort of thing happens at an extreme speed, I don’t see any evidence that that many jobs will be lost within that timeframe. There might be signs of software jobs being lost because of LLM’s, but it’s still not clear whether that is simply a business cycle or if it represents a larger trend. Once self-driving becomes safer than humans driving, I think things will really start picking up steam. But so far, self-driving is proving much more difficult that originally thought. It’s still an open question as to whether we can brute force it with data or whether we need new architectures and maybe even improved infrastructure (clear road lanes, etc.). The point is that making a prediction like this should be done with caution and I think it goes without saying that it’s near impossible to predict the future accurately and consistently. Being to early or too late both have heavy costs.

As a software engineer, I can say that both ChatGPT and Copilot are useful at times, but it doesn’t come remotely close to replacing my job. It is dumber than a sack of beans and has to be spoon-fed with very small tasks that I manually break a larger task into, and each and every function needs to be tested, as it is likely to be wrong.

Sometimes it gets a small task right on the first attempt, but often you have to make repeated prompts explaining exactly what the problem is. If you have the patience, it will eventually make it, but at times it is just easier to do it yourself. It is like a calculator you cannot trust. It does however understand languages both human and computer languages quite well, and it is useful when translating from one computer language to another.

comments.comment_text:
8:04 I was slightly disappointed that you did not mention TU Chemnitz with its M. Sc. Data Science degree. Sure, there are a dozen universities that offer similar programs, but the one in Chemnitz is quite unique, and I'd argue it offers exactly what you need as a future ML engineer. At least when I was researching it three years ago, there was nothing comparable out there.

In contrast to literally any other ML or Data Science program, in TU Chemnitz there are only three mandatory modules: introduction to Data Science, introduction to Neural Networks, and a coding seminar project. All other stuff is elective! This allows you to specialize in whatever topic is most relevant to you, and also to brush up on some topics where you have a knowledge gap. There is a quite impressive list of "regular" lectures you can choose from, which covers almost everything you may need, from heavy maths stuff like Theory of Optimization, to more practival CS stuff like Multiprocesing, and also some niche stuff like Neurocognition or XML Metadata parsing, just to name a few. In addition, every new semester they offer specialized state of the art lectures which are designed from scratch and are only offered once. For example, I took a lecture about solving Inverse Problems with Deep Learning, which is an extremely niche topic, but it was exactly what I needed at the time. And if this is not enough, there are also some "placeholder" modules which you can fill with any other lecture offered by the university, for example you could take a lecture about autonomous driving from the IT department, or some biology lecture, or literally anything else. Machine Learning is not only about machine learning, it is also about domain knowledge and specific use cases, so this freedom allows you to learn something outside of ML bubble to better understand the domain you want to operate in.

comments.comment_text:
This is exactly the point, people think their's a particular thing they have to learn and then they can call themselves "hacker".
cyber security is a diverse field and you have to have a strong background in Networking, Computer Science, Programming, Cyber security laws and policies, and in general an understanding of human psychology (for Social Engineering).
Some of these skills may or may not be relevant to your Job role but knowing them will always help you.
In general hacking is simply the process of making a system do something it is not supposed do, that's how the attacker thinks and to counter him you have to think exactly like him but stay a step ahead of him.
conclusion: Don't look for shortcuts, work on basics (first priciples), and always remember an attacker will have a thousand chances but you'll only have one so be ready and be useful to your organization.

comments.comment_text: In response to ChatGPT's, "I'm just here to help." At the beginning of my work life, I worked on a sort floor (testing micro chips). When I started we were running 1-3 machines. By the time I left 2 years later, we were running at minimum 5 machines (improved automation). Many of us were running 8+. A couple years after I left, the company I worked for eliminated the sorting department. The error rate had dropped so low that testing was deemed unnecessary. AI will continue that process across the workforce. There will be a significant net loss in employment, with the law sector being one of the hardest hit. Trial lawyers will be the last people standing in the sector. Only highly creative jobs and jobs where human to human interaction is highly desired will be safe. Perhaps surprisingly, the last remaining call center operators might be among them.

comments.comment_text:
Certainly great advice here. Yes, narrow AI has some useful applications that will continue to disrupt industries, and one should definitely understand how it is changing one's profession. That said, unless we want a future of mediocrity and disdain, we also need to push back on uninformed concessions to AI, and make sure decision-makers are aware of the risks of relying too heavily on it. Don't support initiatives that destroy the value of work. Elevate the people and processes that have responsible and ethical stances on the technology (few as they may be).

AI is here to stay, but we are very quickly approaching a bubble that is going to seriously damage the all-in crowd. This technology has obvious and severe limitations and is NOT a replacement for empathy, critical thinking, and skills mastery. Play the game where you have to open doors, but don't stop cultivating the skills you need to differentiate yourself from AI in your field. Prediction engines do not innovate, humans do. When everyone eventually offers the same honed AI experience in their industry, the human differentiators that create innovation are what will ultimately drive commerce.

comments.comment_text:
You can’t read much about the risks of advanced AI without soon coming across the paperclip maximizer thought experiment.



First put forward by the Swedish philosopher Nick Bostrom in his 2003 paper “Ethical Issues in Advanced Artificial Intelligence,” the thought experiment goes like this: Imagine an artificial general intelligence (AGI), one essentially limitless in its power and its intelligence. This AGI is programmed by its creators with the goal of producing paperclips. (Why would someone program a powerful AI to create paperclips? Don’t worry about it — the absurdity is the point.)

Because the AGI is superintelligent, it quickly learns how to make paperclips out of anything. And because the AGI is superintelligent, it can anticipate and foil any attempt to stop it — and will do so because its one directive is to make more paperclips. Should we attempt to turn the AGI off, it will fight back because it can’t make more paperclips if it is turned off — and it will win, because it is superintelligent.

The final result? The entire galaxy, including you, me, and everyone we know, has either been destroyed or been transformed into paperclips. (As AI arch-doomer Eliezer Yudkowsky has written: “The AI does not hate you, nor does it love you, but you are made out of atoms which it can use for something else.”) End thought experiment.



The point of the paperclip maximizer experiment is twofold. One, we can expect AIs to be optimizers and maximizers. Given a goal, they will endeavor to find the optimal strategy to fulfill the maximal achievement of that goal, without worrying about the side effects (which in this case involve the galaxy being turned into paperclips).



Two, it’s therefore very important to carefully align the objectives of the AI with what we truly value (which in this case probably does not involve the galaxy more or less being transformed into paperclips). As ChatGPT told me when I asked about the thought experiment, “It underscores the need for ethical considerations and control measures in the development of advanced AI systems.”



Clever as the paperclip maximizer experiment is as an analogy for the problems of AI alignment, it’s always struck me as a little beside the point. Could you really create an AI so superintelligent that it can figure out how to turn every atom in existence into paperclips, but somehow also not smart enough to realize that such a result is not something we, its creators, would intend? There’s really nowhere in this hypothetical artificial brain that would stop somewhere along the way — perhaps after it had turned Jupiter into 2.29 x 1030 paperclips (thank you, ChatGPT, for the calculations) — and think, “Perhaps there are downsides to a universe composed only of paperclips”?
comments.author: @dr.radiobooks

This is probably how things can shake out.

comments.comment_text:
work in writing (words not code) and I think what has happened to us will happen to software people in the next few years. Basically everyone is being changed from being a writer and editor to a "reviewer". Even if the copy is horrible and takes time to clean up, since it was already written by the AI, we are paid a fraction of what you would get as a writer or an editor of human-written work. Moreover the efficiency of AI means there are a lot of people scrambling for fewer, lower paying jobs. A lot of people still cling to the dream that human writers will be sought after more than ever because you can't replace human creativity or that AI will only make us more productive creating more work.

But things haven't been creative for decades. We are churning out garbage product that is why we are easily replaceable. At least as a writer of English, we don't have to worry about offshoring or H1-B visas just yet (but as English becomes the global language it is only a matter of time), which software people do have to worry about. The people clinging to the "human creativity can't be replaced" or "AI will make us more efficient leading to better more visionary jobs" are the ones who are not training and switching to new jobs right now. Don't stay on the Titanic. Yes, there will be a few people with better, more visionary jobs, but they are either lucky or have good connections. The vast majority will be given work that used to be entry level, grind work with little room for promotion. There will just be the need for people to check the AI output for fatal flaws and mistakes. And believe me that is more tedious than the most tedious "human" work.

comments.comment_text:
I got 1, 2, 7, 8, 11, 12, 13, 14, 16 and 17 correct. AI still has its tells, but you have to basically pixel peek to find them now (except for the one with the old lady, was very obviously fake)

I hear the sentiment that AI is developing rapidly, which it is, but no one really asks why that is. While it is true that the techniques behind machine learning has come a long way, the real force driving its improvement is data. We are at a point of diminishing returns (with regards to image generation) right now.

For the next improvement in AI, i think the dataset needs to evolve. For example, depth maps, normal maps, and de-lit diffuse maps would allow for ways to train an AI to understand depth, volume and fine details like wrinkles.

On the technical front - which I have no expertise in, so take this with a grain of salt - there should be some way of explicitly describing an object and its properties. Things like shape and general color. As of now, AI works more like an intelligent guess, stringing words together and pulling images from its database that has the highest likelyhood of being correct. A way of describing an environment and all the things in it could allow for a more versatile outputs.

comments.comment_text:
I never understood why people seemed to be saying what a huge boon it is using Copilot. My personal experience is that it can be but only in limited, specific use cases. It's useful for boilerplate or for helping me figure out roughly how to do something I've never done before and tailoring it a bit to my specific needs. It's useful for showing me well known but technical algorithms or maths equations.

But there's almost always a fatal flaw in the code it gives you that you have to debug and figure out. Often it just completely makes things up. This week for example it showed me how to use the "@continue" directive in SASS, but then only later tells me that the "@continue" directive doesn't exist at all in SASS. It leads me down rabbit holes insisting to me that a certain thing is possible, only for it to turn out that it's definitively not possible.

Even if it's right and you ask it "are you sure xyz exists?" it will often go back and then think it doesn't exist. So you have to go back to googling things either way. It saves time, but usually not a huge amount of time, and only if you use it in the right situations and are good at knowing when to cut your losses and google stuff.

comments.comment_text:
This is all pretty sensible.

I've been telling people since last year that the near future for AI is to take existing LLM technology and wrap extra formal constraints and other code around it to provide reliability and predictability. (And better UX)

My experience using LLMs to write code is almost entirely that they are great at producing code up to a certain size (I guess within the context window) but start to degrade the moment your code gets bigger than that.

And we need copilots that can work on large code-bases.

So augmenting the LLMs with some version of RAG. And, indeed, formal modelling and summarization of code, and querying for relevant subsets of it, is going to be the way forward to make AI-augmented coding scale the way we need it to. There's a lot of more "traditional" tooling to be built before AIs become genuinely comparable to human programmers. And the best news (IMHO) is that the good tools will be like tools that are good for human programmers. I'm thinking maybe ideas like Glamorous Toolkit will get more mainstream. AI-driven tools can run through, annotate, summarize, experimentally run, and otherwise explore larger code-bases to build up a more comprehensive map and higher level overview, which is then small enough to fit into the context window to reason about.

There's going to be a lot of work for real developers as we roll that out. But it will need a different mindset. (And maybe organizational structure)

My heuristic right now is to use AI to write small tools : editor plugins, parsers, data-mungers, Docker files etc. And to do small-scale translations from legacy code into newer languages and frameworks, one module at a time. Then I as a human still combine and apply these tools and translations into making bigger stuff. Eventually AI agents will be able to do some of that larger scale composition too. But the AIs will still need to be managed by tech-savvy developers.
