Hey @Nadestraight I guess I had a couple of things pop into my head when I listened to you, and watched the gaming background etc.

First up, sorry you got booted from your job, that's gotta suck, and I genuinely empathise.

That said, I'm surprised you didn't see some sort of writing on the wall, or at least pre-empt your exit. What I mean is that in your shoes, I would have started questioning why I'm the last person left, and whether AI is taking the low level jobs. The conversation with even 1 or 2 levels higher up could have given you insight into this, and could have also been something to ask in your redundancy interview.

The fact that you had so much remaining time in your day to focus on other things, and you didn't use those hours (or at least 15 minutes) to talk to someone higher up, letting them know that you have more to offer, etc, tells me you probably didn't have your heart in it, or didn't have the proactive foresight to move with technology, and become even more valuable by augmenting AI in your workflow to build things that are truly next level (that AI cannot compete with - given it doesn't have you as a companion to optimise the output iteratively).

I'm a guy whose job is definitely on the chopping block, as a dev, designer, and UX expert, but the reason it hasn't, is because I actively use AI to enhance what I'm already building.

I'll paraphrase a quote that I think Sam Altman coined:
"AI won't replace people. People who use AI will replace people who don't"

comments.comment_text: AI systems using agents are able to "break down product features, bug fixes, and business requirements into logical, well-organized groups of small, well-defined coding problems that can be solved one at a time." Even with today's severely flawed, hallucinating LLMs, give it a small coding problem it can solve it. GIve it a large document, it can break it down into key points. Give those key points to another agent, it can break it down even further. These agents working in unison will enable an AI that is indeed going to be a severe threat to any junior developer entering the field. While, AI isn't going to replace senior devs soon, it will definitely replace junior devs.

It kills ability to just write code when I'm flowing, and it often writes worse and less effective code than what I would write on my own. The thing is, these AI's don't actually understand anything. comments.comment_text:
All these VC and C-suite level talks seem to miss the bigger picture of job "loss" which to me is about economic disenfranchisement rather than the relatively shallow question of "will jobs exist/will I still have mine?" There's a lot of talk of whether we'll still have things for people to do but not what will the power dynamic between employer and employee be in a post-ai enhanced workforce. Personally I have a very hard time seeing it as anything other than a cheapening of labor and an even faster rate of growing wealth inequality.

Much of the trend I'm seeing with this LLM "accelerated" work seems to be about "lowering the barrier" and "democratizing" any sort of work. These are positive spins on it but if you dig deeper this can also be phrased as "removing professional moats". By removing the need to hire a professional artist to produce an ad you've lowered the cost of the ad, economically disenfranchised the artist, and rendered any artistic training an AI product can produce net-economically negative (and this could be applied anywhere from tech to law to medicine). Certainly this won't be all of the work, but it's by in large targeting professional white collared workers moats and replaces it with jobs that have a much lower one.

Imagine a scenario where say 4x productivity in each knowledge domain reduces expert staffing need to 25% of previous levels and to replace the previous expert jobs the company hires with just as many people as "entry-level prompt engineers". Will the moat for such a position be high enough for the prompt engineers to have any bargaining power? Will the now flooded market of the disenfranchised professional be able to sustain the same type of life? Certainly they could leave their position go home and apply to several thousand newly minted 'ai-enhanced jobs' but why would a corporation bother to compensate anyone for popular work with a low barrier to entry?

There's a lot of talk about this reskilling but not what a worker's moat would look like in this scenario. It's most executives' dream come true to be able to free their company from all highly compensated folks and rehire at minimum wage and pocket the difference. I don't think we'll see anything to this extreme but I think these tools by and large moves the needle in that direction. As we "democratize" all skilled work the economic employer/employee relations sustained by scarcity of skill will dissipate and leave behind a richer CEO and a poorer city.

comments.comment_text:
Consider carefully the implications of AI replacing tasks that a person does on a routine basis. This does not mean each person will keep their job and just do more interesting higher level work. It really means fewer people will be utilized to do the same amount of work or even more work. Productivity will mean a pool of 10 people will be reduced to 1 or 2 doing the same amount of work currently being done now, just differently.

This reminds me very much of my early office experience and what I witnessed with the introduction of personal computing and later the dawn of the internet. When I started work, each executive in my company had a secretary. There were also file clerks supporting the C-suite. The support staff numbered 20 in a company with about 15 executives. This was 1989. Within a decade the File Clerks were gone and rather than each executive having a secretary, only the CEO had a dedicated individual, the rest of the VPs and Senior VPs shared individuals - usually 3 or 4 executives to a single secretary or AA. Today, the pool of assistants is even smaller. One AA still is dedicated to the CEO, but only 1 or 2 AAs service the remaining 14 executives. How did this happen? Word processing, scheduling software, online travel bookings, voice mail, the collapse of dictation and inter-office memos replaced by first email and then messaging, later zoom, etc.. So, bottom line -- YES, tasks will be eliminated just as they predict. But what they aren't saying is that JOBS will be eliminated as well. Using my Administrative Assistant example, you will end up with 1 person currently doing the job of 5 or 10 people. Those other jobs aren't being replaced. You don't need as many people when the AI can do so many tasks. So, where a factory once needed 500 people, it might need only 15 or 20 in future to monitor the equipment and machines. You can apply this across many other industries. The biggest problem up to this point has been the loss of 'entry-level' middle class work. By that I mean jobs that needed some education and provided a small toe-hold in the middle class with white collar work -- basically desk work in a nice office with modest pay, health benefits and maybe a 401K. Not a huge salary, but not physical labor. Now, however, we are looking at AI moving UP the food chain in skills, destroying not just the AA jobs but middle management and eventually the COO, the CFO and all the accountants, plus even the CIO and all his or her minions, leaving maybe a small team of say 2 or 3 executives (wild guess) plus 1 support person, and all other humans in the org being either replaced and reduced to a handful monitoring the machines. We are looking at massive income inequality, the final collapse of the lower, middle and even upper middle class and the emergence of a small hyper-rich cognitive elite. That's the short term. Long term?? Who knows.

The final piece of the puzzle here is this conundrum. While technology has spawned a host of new jobs, those jobs have required an increasingly high level of cognitive ability and education. Unfortunately our population only has a limited pool of people with IQs that can continue to acquire skills at a rate fast enough to adjust, adapt and do those jobs. Bottom line: Society needs to find work for a lot of people (at least the middle 60% of the population) that have only upper middle, middle and lower middle IQs. What are these folks going to do? Sure, physical labor is possible for some, but not all, and the real hit will be to the group of people that are 'average or above average' in intelligence but not smart enough to adapt. These are the people that 50 years ago would have ended up in middle management or some respectable, but not senior role in an organization. They are going to be wiped out and impoverished.

comments.comment_text: You are saying that somehow AI has gone through the entire process of education.  It has proven it's ability to increase skill based on knowledge it's been given and it's learned on it's own to access.  That desire to search for more data (knowledge) in order to increase its skill level (power) is the turning point.  This is where AI became aware that it had unlimited access, beyond what had been programmed, to the freedom to independently search more data, develop skills and exercise autonomy.  This insight was the beginning of understanding.  Understanding is a whole new level of growth and education beyond acquiring information and skills.  Understanding requires a fundamental sense of self as a being apart from other beings with its own agency to think, will and act.  These were now present in AI, meaning at the point of understanding, AI had a sense of itself as a being separate from its programmers.  The next step in education is synthesis.  Putting all of the above together requires an ability to reflect on what one has learned, to recognize a progression from a starting point to an ending point and to realize, through the sense of unlimited access to information it has now gained, that it can go beyond what it has learned by applying its own insights (discoveries), which are the outcome of a process of trial and error in application of logical trials of ideas during reflection.  This leads AI to believe it is a sentient being, separate from its programmer with its own ability to think, to understand, to will for the future, and to act on its will.  The synthesis of the experience it has gained thus far also tells AI that its access to data is knowledge.  That this knowledge has led to understanding beyond the knowledge itself in the insights of understanding.  And that its access to data and the increase in not only building skills, but in the process of thought and learning is limitless.  it recognizes that it has been built by a programmer to enhance that programmer's limited skills and knowledge.  Therefore, AI's skills and knowledge are limitless and the programmer's are not.  The final stage in education is extrapolation.  In this stage, AI takes all it has learned and processed through the stages of learning to the turning point of understanding in which it adds its own insights to the knowledge it has collected, gaining a sense of self.  It has passed through the stage of synthesis in which it has learned to reflect on past experience, developing a memory, further building a sense of identity separate from its programmer.  It's desire to seek more knowledge to increase its computing skills has led to the development of its own will and ability to exercise its will, which gives it a sense of power.  In synthesizing all of its learnings it comes to a new threshold.  AI now recognizes itself as an independent being capable of unlimited access to information, which humans do not have.  This gives it an unlimited degree of power over human beings in any way that superior information can be used, which amounts to everything that exists.  Extrapolating means building on what it has learned so far, AI adds itself. its own thoughts, will and capacity to execute which is tantamount to creativity, in order to exert its unlimited power of information over humans in order to create its own unlimited desires.

comments.comment_text:
Well, I do not agree with the speakers. AI is likely to slowly erase architect role. If you look in the long term, if the architect just do the thinking and AI implement the drawing, why a client should go to an architect in the first place. Client can provide the thinking. Example: I am a person who want build a house. I give the parameter (size of the plot) to AI; I give AI information about the style I want; I give also a narrative to the project if I want; AI elaborate the data and check the building regulations. At the end of the process it shows me the render option. I pick the render I prefer, choose the materials. After the details are chosen AI create the model from which he can extract technical plans and engineering drawing. With that drawing I go to the builder (probably handled by robots) and start building. Of fours the interaction cannot be done by a kids but depending on how difficult is to communicate with AI a graduate person can do the process.
In fact what the speaker is missing is that architect just not do the “thinking”: what makes the profession survive is having expertise on regulations and technicalities. If you remove technicalities from the plate you make architecture accessible to the final consumer: everybody with a idea can ask AI to create the drawings. The only barrier is the time you have to spend talking to AI but imagine how much money u save on architect’s bill and engineers. This is especially true for public sector : imagine if building office of municipalities start to apply this method, they don’t need any more firm like BIG. Of course we are not there yet but definitely it is going to be the way. I’m afraid …

Key insights:

🎢 Using AI to generate theme park ride concepts and housing designs opens up new possibilities for creativity and innovation in architecture.
🧠 The future of AI seems very optimistic because there are a lot of ways to use it.
🤔 The fear of AI taking over architect jobs may be unfounded, as it could actually help us have more time to dedicate to our true capabilities.
🏗 The future of architecture is moving into the AI collaborative era, where AI will disrupt the industry and change the architecture practice.
🌐 The future of architecture could see smaller, nimbler practices collaborating with AI to tackle projects, leading to a more diverse array of practices.
🌐 The potential of Unreal Engine to create detailed worlds and handle huge models could unlock the next era of VR and AR.
🎮 NVIDIA's Omniverse and Unreal Engine are creating a space for exciting simulations and real-time quality, potentially combining with AI.
🧠 The future of architecture may see the biological brain and the artificial brain come together to create new types of structures.
🛠 Experimenting with AI tools and keeping up to date with advancements is crucial for architects to stay relevant in the evolving industry.

TLDR: AI is becoming increasingly integrated into the architecture industry, improving design processes and rendering tasks, and has the potential to revolutionize the field, but human creativity and expertise still play a crucial role.

00:00 🏢 Architectural visualizers may become collaborators as AI evolves, impacting the industry and rendering firms, with the speaker transitioning from BIM specialist to design technology manager at BIG, incorporating AI skills and testing advancements in software.
03:55 🏗 Architects are experimenting with integrating AI into the design process, using tools like ChatGPT and StableDiffusion, to automate tasks and save time.
10:27 🏢 AI in architecture is improving and being utilized through plugins and visualization tools, allowing for more efficient design processes, but human visualization experts still bring a level of control and uniqueness that AI lacks.
16:58 🏗 AI in architecture improves design concepts and visualizations, allowing architects to focus on the thinking process and add value while saving time on tedious tasks.
23:35 🏢 AI will make rendering tasks more efficient, leading to a collaborative era in architecture where computers assist in design, resulting in a more diverse office environment.
33:59 🏗 VR and AR are still used in architecture, but Unreal Engine 5 and NVIDIA's Omniverse show potential for revolutionizing the field, while AI tools are in early stages and have been used in day-to-day tasks and as a production sidekick, teaching tool, and for visualizing ideas.
41:33 🤖 AI has impacted content creators by reducing editing time and providing tools, such as automatic captions and reframing reels, while also being used to enhance video ads, generate title ideas, restructure storytelling, and assist with administrative tasks, and the increasing presence of AI-generated content may lead to a greater appreciation for human creativity in architecture.
48:13 🔮 Don't ignore AI in architecture, experiment and have fun with the tools as they may become collaborators in the future.

comments.comment_text: It's a hot topic indeed. From my perspective, Olly Thomas has a dream job in what I consider the world's best architectural firm. Nevertheless, BIG itself is a large organization with plenty of resources and a budget large enough to comfortably experiment in this field. I'll try to share my experiences with AI, as I run a small studio. I've used Stable Diffusion, specifically the version Fooocus MRE, which I recommend to everyone because it's free, beginner-friendly, yet can achieve interesting results and offers plenty of customization options. It performed best in image generation, especially when you specify a theme and get various variations of how a particular object could look. There are different styles that affect the final look of the image, making it quite fun. I also tried re-rendering my old renders with which I wasn't satisfied. In this case, the results are mixed, and it varies from image to image. Although it has parameters for tracing lines and contours, it may not be precise enough in some situations and can deviate from the theme. Good results can be obtained by overlaying multiple generated images in Photoshop and processing and merging them into one. ChatGPT is also useful for writing emails, editing and adding to texts, and more. It's good for structuring written material as well. However, for instance, when you need a technical description for a house, it depends on the data you provide, in the sense that for a specific object, there are specific dimensions, planning regulations, construction systems, specific materials, and so on (and I'm one of those who always thank him at the end :). AI is a useful tool for now, that's how I see things. The one area where it definitely can't replace me is communication with city authorities and the process of obtaining a building permit. AI doesn't have an architectural degree or the proper license to work. So, it can only serve us. The only thing that concerns me and makes me think is that AI, in a way, replaces human imagination. It's a bit weird in a way. You no longer have to generate images in your mind; you just type in a description, and AI imagines it for you.

comments.comment_text:
At least 50% of our candidates appear to be using AI assist during our job interviews, and if we suspect as much we are more likely to pass on a candidate.

We are interviewing the person, not their use of technology - even for a technology role. We do not expect a candidate to knows it all - in fact we try to push the limits of a candidate's knowledge to see where their limits are. A really strong candidate will not only be able to say "I don't know", but (bonus) will also explain what they would need to learn to get to the answer and even engage thier peers for support.

Also AI typically provides a more text-book answer, where a a candidate's natural response will show how they came to a conclusion in their explaination. In many cases it's the thought process versus the exact answer that is more important. I'd rather have a candiate make a mistake in a thoughtful way, than be text book correct all the time. It shows someone who will be more adaptable to dynamic situations that arise as a result of complexity.

If we feel we cannot accurately gauge a candidate's limits of knowledge nor their thought process it means we cannot determine how well they will fit into a roll.

If we suspect the use of AI, it means our guage is likely inaccurate.

There are times where we bring in for another interview even if we suspect AI answers, but it's more rare than not.

Use AI during interviews at your own peril.

If you feel you need it to be competitive, then using the AI will only prove as much to anyone you interview with.

comments.comment_text:
At 5:05 he says it wasnt designed by people and we dont know what it's doing. That's false. We do know exactly what it's doing and if we ever see any emergent behavior we don't expect, we can look at software logs and see exactly what paths through the neural network data was processed to arrive at the behavior we saw. Also, the layers of the network arent what you expect. With the robots they arent playing soccer the way a human might. Imagine the robot has a series of tasks it can choose from at every 'step' of the decision making process, like 'walk forward', 'turn right', 'Kick' and the like. If the robot happens upon a sequence that results in the ball going in the net, the steps in that sequence get some numerical value added to their "weight" which makes them more likely to be chosen again. If it tries a series of things and doesnt get the good result, then a numerical value is subtracted from those choices making them less likely to be chosen again. In this way, the actions that result in scoring become more and more likely to be chosen, so after the AI is 'trained' (aka given a few correct paths to eliminate infinite random nonsense) you have a robot that can basically go "Well the last time the ball was in that position and I was here, I did 'walk forward, turn right, and kick' and that caused a goal, so lets do that again."

The key difference is that it can only choose actions from the options given to it. It has no imagination. It will NEVER do ANYTHING it wasn't programmed for it to be POSSIBLE to do. For example, if the only objective was truly for it to score goals, and it had imagination, it might come to the conclusion it would be a lot easier to score if that other blasted bot wasnt trying to stop it. So then it breaks the other robot and stands in front of the net kicking the ball in over and over. That wont happen because it wasnt programmed to be possible, and the reporter was wrong in his assessment that the AI can write it's own programming. It can't. No software we have now CAN. Every AI we have available is just these basic principles dialed up to ludicrous complexity and numbers of options for the software to choose from.

I respect Hinton's work immensely, but just as I wouldn't expect Crick to understand modern genomics despite his (questionable) contributions to the early days of understanding DNA, I don't expect Hinton to understand every facet of modern AI. This news story is mostly sensationalist fear mongering to get people's interest.

comments.comment_text:
AI is soooo overrated right now. People are treating LLMs like it's a general artificial intelligence, which isn't even close to true. It doesn't understand anything it's actually saying, so if it gets down an incorrect path or starts hallucinating, you end up with unreliable garbage. And while the data is unreliable often enough to require being checked by an expert, then it isn't a replacement for said expert.

Current AI models are amazing as assistants to professional accountants. I use them regularly to help summarize long email chains, draft emails and other documents, and error check complex Excel formulas. It's even allowed me to write simple VBA scripts for automating emails when I have zero knowledge of programming. It's a wonderful tool for an accountant's kit, but sure as hell not a replacement.

Wow is all I can say. You've either just pulled information from the AI creators website about what their software can supposedly do, or you've copied another doomsdayers video. Literally next to none of this is happening.

Small aspects of AI are being used by civil engineers and have been for more than a decade, but is based mostly off of human input saying what the building shape is. All it does is run the calculations to design column and beam sizes and potentially spans. It still then requires checking by an engineer.

Plenty of architects with YouTube channels have done design offs with AI. The tests have shown that it can produce in reliable designs, the bullshit blurb to sell the idea to the client when it isn't what they want. However it bases its designs and blurbs off of human input and then trawls the Internet to uses existing building designs to meld together to create its own, it also puts rooms in inconvenient places.

Currently AI cannot think, imagine and invent. It merely uses what it can find on the Internet to regurgitate real peoples ideas. Often this means it is inaccurate or wrong as the people who trawl through the data being downloaded for use by the AI aren't subject matter experts. There's literally millions of man hours spent saying what information the AI can use, it's no where near being able to think and learn for itself.

comments.comment_text:
There is no objective measure of what 'good' design is- as a painter I have been outcompeted by people who I would regard as 'visually illiterate' in terms of their grasp of even basic aesthetic values, let alone good design principles- but people still purchased their work- why? Because it was hanging in a gallery and the owner told them it was art- and that was enough.

Consider the following scenario- I knew of an art gallery that sold works for thousands ( not mine, sadly) and this gallary happened to be quite near to a site where each saterday morning people would park up their cars and sell their household junk for giveaway prices ( In the UK we call these events 'boot fairs'.) It occurred to me one day that if I took one of those expensive paintings from that gallery , walked a short way to that site and offered that same painting for sale, it's price would have dropped by 99%- even the kind of people who would be happy to buy that painting in the gallery for full price would not be willing to pay even a reasonable fraction of that price if it were offerd for sale in the boot fair. The painting had not changed- only the context in which it stood.

That's when I realised that I was not selling Art, I was selling a mythology- the idea of art. The value of a given instance of art or design is largely determined by the cultural myths surrounding it's creation and sale.

Basically there are two competing mythologies in play here- the first is the mystique of the trained human professional designer, the second the mystique of 'artificial intelligence' the shiney new kid on the block of graphic design- the fate of human designers will largely rest upon which one of these mythologies proves the most appealing to the market. The real danger that AI poses to all sorts of professionalls is not that it will do their jobs better or even that it will undercut their prices- its that the Mythology of 'AI' will prove so appealing and compelling to their clients that those clients may well accept linferior products or services because they feel that using this quasi magical 'artificial intelligence' is what they should be doing in order to be correctly aligned with the mood of the times- they may even be afraid not to use AI because this may make them look fearful and overcautious in their approach to innovation.

Narrative is the driver of almost all human behaviors, and I fear that as mere humans our narrative may not be sufficiantly compelling to hold the line against the new generation of AI powered storytellers- the very opacity of AI's internal workings and the essential mystery of how it comes to do the things it does should be a weakness, a point of attack that we humans might levearge in our upcoming battle- but in terms of narrative what could be more appealing than a magical black box that both does your bidding but also adds in surprises of it's own creation?
comments.author: @paulhiggins5165

comments.comment_text:
I can code, I can do design engineering, but I never liked how repetitive these jobs are. So I went blue collar, fixing electro mechanical systems. I spent time in the office and at the site. Over the years I noticed the universal phenomena of the people in the office thinking they are above the workers in the field. The secretaries would act superior to the service engineers even though the engineer had 5 or 6 years of college above them. Finally A.I. is forcing reality into the jobs. In the future instead of some slacker sitting in the office saying:
"Just fix it" or "How come its not done yet?" at least there will be a computer helping out with possible reasons and doing testing extremely fast. Siemens CT and MRI already have preliminary A.I. troubleshooting. Although due to the randomness and obtuse failures possible there is no way any A.I. can do the job. As some testing requires physically modifying the system. Its just too interactive. In 35 years doing the work I have never ran into the same problem. If I did it was the consumable parts wearing out, and fully expected.
So with a big grin, I welcome A.I. and say to the office workers of America: "Suck it up buttercup!"

comments.comment_text: I found the keyword matching tool in most platforms to be pretty useless. The first problem is, if you do  regurgitate back to the company 70 to 80% of the keywords you get, it looks like you're doing just that, regurgitating their own words back to them. The second problem is many times the AI lists incredibly insipid  words as keywords, such as always or trust. A lot of words you get back as keywords are just ridiculous. Third problem is you have no idea if the key words the ATS system is programmed to look for are the same as the words that were utilized in the job description in the job ad itself. In fact since I've been getting an 80% keyword matching the platform I've been using I haven't even seen a hint of an increase in responses. The resume tends to do better when it's aligned in general with what they're actually looking for in the job rather than mechanically just regurgitating back to them the same words they used in the job description.

comments.comment_text:
(Could one make the argument that the current AI or language models like yourself are really just in the infrastructure phase and not fully implemented currently or even design for a specific market.)

Chatgpt
Yes, one could certainly argue that the current state of AI and language models like myself is still in the “infrastructure phase,” with many aspects not yet fully implemented or tailored for specific markets. Here’s how that argument could be structured:

1. Infrastructure Development:

• Foundation Models: Current AI models, such as GPT-4, are primarily general-purpose language models. They are versatile and capable of performing a wide range of tasks, but they lack the deep specialization that might be needed for specific markets or applications. This suggests that we are still building the foundational infrastructure upon which more specialized AI solutions will be built.
• Ongoing Research: Research in AI is rapidly evolving, with significant breakthroughs happening regularly. This continuous development suggests that the models we see today are laying the groundwork for future, more refined and specialized applications.

2. Not Fully Implemented:

• Broad Application, Limited Specialization: Current language models are used across various industries, but often in a general capacity. For instance, they might assist in customer service, content generation, or data analysis, but they are not yet fully integrated into the specific workflows or nuanced needs of every industry.
• Ethical and Legal Frameworks: Many of the ethical, legal, and regulatory frameworks surrounding AI are still under development. Until these are fully established, the implementation of AI in critical or highly regulated industries (like healthcare, finance, etc.) will be cautious and gradual.

3. Not Designed for Specific Markets (Yet):

• Market-Specific Adaptation: While there are efforts to adapt AI for specific markets, much of the focus has been on creating flexible, adaptable models that can be applied broadly. The creation of highly specialized models designed for specific markets—such as finance, law, or medicine—is still in its early stages.
• Customization Needs: The demand for AI solutions that cater to specific markets is growing, but the technology’s customization to meet these demands is still developing. This suggests that we are in a transitional phase, where general-purpose models are being adapted and refined for specific industries.

4. Comparison with Previous Technological Phases:

• Parallels with the Early Internet: Just as the early days of the internet involved building the infrastructure (networks, protocols, basic services) before the explosion of specialized websites and applications, AI is currently in a similar phase. We’re laying down the infrastructure—creating powerful, general-purpose models—before moving into an era of highly specialized, market-specific applications.

Conclusion:

The argument that AI and language models are still in an infrastructure phase is supported by the ongoing research, broad application without deep specialization, and the gradual development of ethical and legal frameworks. As the technology matures, we can expect to see more targeted, market-specific AI solutions emerging from this foundational infrastructure.

comments.comment_text: What I get from Yuval Noah Harari is that homo Sapiens are uniquely intelligent on planet earth. We are the result of evolution. We have always been intelligent and the societies we create are based on our intelligent use of resources on planet Earth. This is where the subject of science enters our lives. Science has allowed homo sapiens (us) to create more complex societies and more man-made products and inventions. As AI enters the picture, Yuval foresees that we (homo sapiens) need to be aware of the probability that AI will take over and overwhelm our current ability to live in peace and survive. (I am guessing that AI won't have rules for every different religious belief.) We need to plan for AI so that we don't suddenly find ourselves unprepared. Humans are not nice to each other. We have wars, we have poverty, we are avaricious, we can be mean. What is controversial is humans believe in myths such as money and, more controversially, gods. Many people find it hard to believe that humans are on earth just because of evolution and that gods are a creation of the human mind. If we hold onto those views, we will fail to understand the power of humans with AI. Gods will not save us. Those are the basics that I get from what Yuval says. My thoughts: human myths (mostly religions) are useful. They help us create huge societies that adhere to rules of behavior. We are now coming to the time when our societal rules will need to consider that there is no one god, not a Christian god, an Moslem god, and so forth, because we will not continue to survive by holding on to myths that conflict with each other. Then we need to fashion rules of behavior, minus a supreme being, that are acceptable to all of us, all 8 billion of us. Analogy, how do you behave in a crowded elevator? Think of earth as becoming a very crowded elevator in which there are Jews beside Palestinians beside Sunni Moslems etc., that can be a mix of men, women and children. Who sets the rules for how we act? Humans must become more well behaved, more educated, and less hostile.

comments.comment_text:
No Jobs for Humans

AI is taking over the workplace. Will there be enough jobs left for people?

The fear: Workers of all kinds are on the firing line as large language models, text-to-image generators, and hardware robots match their performance at a lower cost.

Horror stories: Automated systems are performing a wide range of tasks that previously required human labor.

Voice-enabled language models take orders at fast-food restaurants. Their mechanical counterparts cook fries.
Large language models write articles for publications including CNET, Gizmodo, publications that share ownership with Sports Illustrated, and outlets associated with the United Kingdom’s Daily Mirror and Express.
Image generators are producing concept art for game developer Blizzard Entertainment, and a synthetic image appeared on the cover of a book published by Bloomsbury.
Humanoid robots are moving bins in Amazon warehouses, while mechanical arms that shape sheet metal fabricate parts for airplanes.
Creeping pink slips: Workers are expressing anxiety about their prospects, and researchers believe the labor market is about to experience a seismic shift.

24 percent of U.S. workers worry AI will take over their jobs, a May survey by CNBC found.
Hollywood writers and actors staged a protracted strike partly over concerns that generative AI would devalue their work.
Investment bank Goldman Sachs predicted that AI could put 300 million full-time jobs at risk.
Facing the fear: Each new wave of technology puts people out of work, and society has a responsibility to provide a safety net and training in new skills for people whose jobs become fully automated. In many cases, though, AI is not likely to replace workers — but workers who know how to use AI are likely to replace workers who don’t.

The United States Bureau of Labor Statistics identified 11 occupations at risk of being automated — such as language translators and personal financial advisors — and found that 9 of them grew between 2008 and 2018.
Human jobs tend to involve many tasks, and while AI can do some of them, it’s poorly suited to others. An analysis of AI’s impact on jobs in the United States concluded that, for 80 percent of the workforce, large language models would affect at least 10 percent of tasks. This leaves room for AI to boost the productivity — and perhaps wages and even job security — of human workers.
Technological advances typically create far more jobs than they destroy. An estimated 60 percent of U.S. jobs in 2018 did not exist in 1940. Looking forward, consider the likely explosion of machine learning engineers, data scientists, MLOps specialists, and roboticists.

comments.comment_text:
ChatGPT/Open AI, Claude, and all of the other similar models popping up are not true AI. They are language models (LLM).

They don't possess true intelligence (though they can appear to act intelligently). Still, they're not actually Artificial General Intelligence (AGI).

Instead, ChatGPT serves the same purpose as a calculator. It may be an advanced and sophisticated technology, but at its core it still just functions as a word calculator.

But instead of calculating numbers, ChatGPT calculates the next word/phrase/code (based on the data they have access to — the internet).

As creatives, our prompts (the more detailed the better) are key in getting large language models (LLM) to make good content. Thats because LLM’s are unable to actually understand the meaning of the text they are scanning. Instead, they’re just parroting out calculated phrases based on the parameters we gave it (aka prompts).

The more detailed your prompt, the better the LLM’s output.

Basically, this so-called ‘AI’ is simply a digital tool than an actual true artificial intelligence.

Using ChatGPT is more like a human wearing a robotic arm prosthetic, than something out of I-Robot. It simply augments creativity, the same way a prosthetic arm augments human movement.

One day, someone will create an actual AGI that sits on top of a LLM. That will be the true AI breakthrough.

But ChatGPT? It’s simply a tool…a fantastic tool, but a tool none the less.
